
-- Rewrite metaphors and affirmations in TJ Anderson voice for Infection Control

-- Block 1
UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'Bacteria are everywhere, on your skin, in the air, on every surface you touch. Some of them are working with your body, helping you stay balanced. Others are waiting for an opening, a crack in your defenses, to cause real harm. This is why your sanitation routine is not just a checklist. It is your professional boundary. The same way you decide who gets access to your energy, you decide what gets access to your tools and your clients. Single celled organisms that exist everywhere are only dangerous when you stop paying attention.',
  affirmation = 'I set boundaries in my workspace the same way I set them in my life. I decide what gets through. My sanitation practice is my professional standard, and I hold it with confidence.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Bacteria';

UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'A virus cannot survive on its own. It needs a living cell to reproduce, to multiply, to become something bigger than it started. Think about that. Without a host, a virus has no power. It is completely dependent. This is why prevention matters more than treatment when it comes to viral infections. Antibiotics cannot touch a virus because it is not a living cell like bacteria. Your power is in stopping it before it ever finds a home. Sanitation is not just cleaning. It is cutting off access.',
  affirmation = 'I do not wait for problems to show up before I protect my space. I prevent. I prepare. I am the barrier between risk and my client, and that barrier holds.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Virus';

UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'Fungi love the conditions most people ignore, warm, damp, forgotten spaces. A tool left wet in a drawer. A surface wiped but never dried. Molds, mildews, and yeasts thrive where attention fades. Athlete''s foot and ringworm do not come from nowhere. They come from environments that were not maintained. Your workspace reflects your standards. When you keep things clean and dry, you are not just following a rule. You are protecting your clients from organisms that grow in neglect.',
  affirmation = 'I maintain my environment with the same care I bring to my craft. I do not let neglect create space for harm. My workspace reflects who I am as a professional.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Fungus';

UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'A parasite takes without giving. It attaches to a host, feeds off that host, and offers nothing in return. Head lice on a client''s scalp are feeding on blood. They are surviving because of someone else''s body. You have probably met people like this in life, those who drain your energy and give nothing back. In your salon, your job is to recognize the signs early and protect your space. Screening your clients and maintaining sanitation is how you stop parasites from spreading through your environment.',
  affirmation = 'I protect my clients and my space from anything that takes without giving. I recognize the signs. I trust my training. I respond with confidence and professionalism.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Parasite';

UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'Not every microorganism is out to harm you. But the ones that are, those are pathogens. Certain bacteria, certain viruses, certain fungi, certain parasites, they have the ability to cause disease when they enter the body and multiply. Your entire infection control practice exists because of pathogens. Every time you clean, disinfect, and follow protocol, you are standing between a pathogen and your client. You are the gatekeeper. And gatekeepers do not take days off.',
  affirmation = 'I am the gatekeeper of my workspace. I stand between harm and the people who trust me with their care. My infection control practice is my professional promise.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Pathogen';

-- Block 2
UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'Not all bacteria are the enemy. Nonpathogenic bacteria live on your skin right now, quietly doing their part without causing any harm. Some of them actually support your body''s normal processes. They are like the people in your life who show up, do good work, and never ask for recognition. The key is knowing the difference between what is helping and what is hurting. That discernment, that ability to tell nonpathogenic from pathogenic, is what separates a good student from a great professional.',
  affirmation = 'I know the difference between what helps and what harms. I do not treat everything as a threat. I lead with knowledge, not fear, and that makes me stronger.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Nonpathogenic Bacteria';

UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'Pathogenic bacteria are the ones that cause real damage. They enter through cuts, through abrasions, through contaminated tools, and once they are in, they multiply fast. In a salon where tools are shared between clients, one missed step in your sanitation routine can open the door to infection. Think of pathogenic bacteria as the consequence of carelessness. Not yours specifically, but anyone''s. Your job is to make sure that in your chair, in your space, that door stays locked.',
  affirmation = 'I do not leave doors open for harm. My sanitation is thorough, intentional, and consistent. Every client who sits in my chair is protected by my standards.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Pathogenic Bacteria';

UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'Cocci are round. That is the first thing to remember. Round shaped bacteria that cluster together in groups, responsible for infections like strep throat that spread through contact, coughing, and contaminated surfaces. When you picture cocci, picture little spheres gathered together, small but capable of causing serious problems when they travel. The shape tells the story. Round, clustered, contagious. Your understanding of that shape is part of how you protect your clients.',
  affirmation = 'I see the details others overlook. I know the shapes, the names, the patterns. My knowledge of cocci is not memorization. It is understanding, and understanding is power.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Cocci';

UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'Bacilli are rod shaped, and they are everywhere. In the dust settling on your station. In the soil tracked in on shoes. In the water and the air. Some bacilli are completely harmless. Others can cause disease when they enter the body through wounds or contaminated surfaces. The point is not to be afraid of them. The point is to respect how common they are and to clean accordingly. Rod shaped bacteria in dust, soil, water, and air. That is your reason to never skip a wipe down.',
  affirmation = 'I respect what I cannot see. I clean with intention, not because I am told to, but because I understand what lives on the surfaces around me.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Bacilli';

UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'Spirilla are the spiral shaped bacteria, the ones that twist and move through liquid with purpose. They are less common than cocci and bacilli, but when they show up, they can cause serious infections. Their shape gives them movement, and movement means they can travel. Think of spirilla as a reminder that bacteria are not all the same. Round, rod, spiral. Each shape behaves differently. Each one requires your awareness. Knowing the three bacterial shapes is knowing the language of infection control.',
  affirmation = 'I speak the language of my profession. I know the shapes, I know the risks, and I carry that knowledge with quiet confidence every single day.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Spirilla';

-- Block 3
UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'Flagella are the reason certain bacteria can move through liquid. These long, thread like structures extend from the cell and spin like a motor, pushing the bacteria forward wherever moisture is present. That is why standing water on your tools or wet surfaces left unattended are not just messy. They are highways for bacteria with flagella to travel. When you dry your tools and keep your workspace free of standing moisture, you are shutting down the road.',
  affirmation = 'I do not give bacteria a way to travel. I keep my tools dry, my surfaces clean, and my standards high. My awareness protects my clients.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Flagella';

UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'An infection begins when harmful microorganisms get past your body''s defenses, settle in, and start multiplying. The body does not stay quiet about it. It responds with redness, swelling, heat, and pain. Those are not just symptoms. They are signals. The body is saying something got through and I am fighting back. As a professional, you need to recognize those signals in your clients and understand that your sanitation practices are what prevent that fight from ever starting.',
  affirmation = 'I read the signals. I understand what the body is telling me. And I know that my infection control practice is the first line of defense before the body ever has to fight.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Infection';

UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'A contagious disease does not stay in one place. It moves from person to person through direct contact, indirect contact, or contaminated surfaces. In a salon where you are touching clients, sharing spaces, and using tools on multiple people, the potential for spread is real. Your infection control procedures are what stop that chain of transmission. You are not just protecting one client. You are protecting every client who comes after them.',
  affirmation = 'I break the chain. My procedures protect not just the person in my chair, but every person who will sit there after. I take that responsibility seriously.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Contagious Disease';

UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'Inflammation is your body''s alarm system. Redness, heat, swelling, and pain are not the problem. They are the response to the problem. The body is increasing blood flow, sending white blood cells to the area, and beginning the healing process. When you see those four signs, redness, heat, swelling, pain, you are looking at a body that is actively protecting itself. Your job is to understand what triggered that alarm and to make sure your practices never become the cause.',
  affirmation = 'I honor my body''s wisdom. I recognize the four signs of inflammation and I understand what they mean. My knowledge keeps me and my clients safe.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Inflammation';

UPDATE public.terms SET
  metaphor = 'Pus is what remains after the battle. Dead white blood cells, destroyed bacteria, tissue debris, all collected in one place. It is not pleasant, but it is evidence that the body showed up and fought. The immune system sent its soldiers, and this is the aftermath. When you see pus, you are seeing proof that the body''s defense system is working. Your role as a professional is to follow proper protocols when you encounter it and never to treat it casually.',
  affirmation = 'I do not look away from what is uncomfortable. I understand what pus represents, and I respond with professionalism, knowledge, and care.'
WHERE section_id = 'c3d4e5f6-a7b8-9012-cdef-ab3456789012' AND term = 'Pus';
